<strong><dfn><i>n</i>-Vision</dfn></strong>
is a real-time, 3D, interactive visualization
system for exploring multivariate functions.<p>
<strong><dfn>AutoVisual</dfn></strong> is a
rule-based system that designs <i>n</i>-Vision visualizations.
<p>
Together, they comprise my thesis work.
<p>

<!WA4><a href="http://www.cs.columbia.edu/graphics/projects/AutoVisual/AutoVisual.html">
<!WA5><img src="http://www.cs.columbia.edu/~beshers/images/nvemboss.gif">
More on <i>n</i>-Vision and AutoVisual</a>

<p><hr><p>

In the past, I worked on FourSight, a system that displayed
four-dimensional objects on a 3D graphics workstation in real time.  I
used Gouraud shading to implement 4D depth cueing: bright parts 
are closer in 4-space, dark parts are further away.  Follow this link
to see more:<p>

<!WA6><a href="http://www.cs.columbia.edu/~beshers/4d.html"><!WA7><img src="http://www.cs.columbia.edu/~beshers/images/4demboss.gif">
 Four dimensional animation with FourSight.</a>


